++++++-## 2026-06-23 — Intent-Based Routing Table
++++++-
++++++-### Date
++++++-2026-06-23
++++++-
++++++-### Source
++++++-`#provenance: root/BUILD_LOG.md` (Phase 5 + Decision D005)
++++++-
++++++-### Decision
++++++-Train the Orchestrator to classify user intent (rather than match keywords) when routing tasks to specialist personas.
++++++-
++++++-### Reasoning
++++++-Early routing used keyword matching. If the user said "I need financial data on Tesla," the keyword "financial" correctly routed to Financial Analyst. But "What's Tesla's P/E ratio?" had no keyword match — it fell through to "handle locally," which meant the Orchestrator guessed, often incorrectly.
++++++-
++++++-Additionally, initial routing had no validation criteria per destination — the only check was "output exists." A persona could return garbage and pass validation.
++++++-
++++++-### Changes Made
++++++-- Replaced keyword routing with intent classification in the Orchestrator's memory
++++++-- Added example phrases for each routing destination
++++++-- Added disambiguation rules for borderline cases (e.g., "if the request involves both financial data and narrative explanation, route to Financial Analyst for data and Research Analyst for narrative")
++++++-- Added a fallback rule: "If uncertain, ask the user to clarify rather than guessing"
++++++-- Defined validation criteria per routing destination:
++++++-  - Financial outputs must cite data sources
++++++-  - Research outputs must include URLs
++++++-  - Code outputs must execute without errors
++++++-  - Operations outputs must include actionable items
++++++-
++++++-### Lessons Learned
++++++-- **Validate early, validate often.** Our first pass had no validation. The second pass had format-only validation. The third pass added content validation. Start with content validation from day one.
++++++-- **Write validation criteria simultaneously with routing rules.** They're two sides of the same coin. Writing them separately meant we had routing without validation for too long.
++++++-- Intent classification is more robust than keyword matching but requires maintaining the example phrase list.
++++++-- Keyword matching was a dead end — it worked for obvious cases and failed for edge cases, which is the worst reliability profile.
++++++-
++++++-### Follow-Up Actions
++++++-- Periodically expand the example phrase list for each routing destination
++++++-- Add adversarial test cases to validate routing robustness
++++++-- Consider whether validation criteria should be version-controlled alongside the routing table
++++++-
